You can use a comparator to sort your stream elements. Also, you can create comparator with a few rules by calling method `firstComparator.thenComparing(secondComparator)`. See example. For input, we have numbers: `[2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 8, 9, 10]`. For output, we will have: `[2, 4, 8, 10, 3, 9, 5, 7]`. First, we put even numbers. Then we put numbers divisible by three. And then we put other numbers.

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List&lt;Integer&gt; sourceList = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 8, 9, 10));

        Comparator&lt;Integer&gt; firstComparator = new Comparator&lt;Integer&gt;() {
            @Override
            public int compare(Integer o1, Integer o2) {
                if (o1 % 2 == 0 &amp;&amp; o2 % 2 == 0 || o1 % 2 != 0 &amp;&amp; o2 % 2 != 0) {
                    return 0;
                }
                if (o1 % 2 == 0) {
                    return -1;
                }
                return 1;
            }
        };

        Comparator&lt;Integer&gt; secondComparator = new Comparator&lt;Integer&gt;() {
            @Override
            public int compare(Integer o1, Integer o2) {
                if (o1 % 3 == 0 &amp;&amp; o2 % 3 == 0 || o1 % 3 != 0 &amp;&amp; o2 % 3 != 0) {
                    return 0;
                }
                if (o1 % 3 == 0) {
                    return -1;
                }
                return 1;
            }
        };

        List&lt;Integer&gt; sortedList = sourceList
                .stream()
                .sorted(firstComparator.thenComparing(secondComparator)
                .collect(Collectors.toList());

        System.out.println(sortedList);
    }

